The '''Chomsky–Foucault debate''' was a [[debate]] about [[human nature]], between [[Noam Chomsky]] and [[Michel Foucault]] in the [[Netherlands]], in November 1971. Chomsky and Foucault were invited by the Dutch philosopher [[Fons Elders]] to discuss an age-old question: "is there such a thing as "innate" [[human nature]] independent of our experiences and external influences?"<ref>{{cite web|title=Noam Chomsky & Michel Foucault Debate - 'On human nature' |date=1971|url=https://www.onscenes.com/video/-noam-chomsky-michel-foucault-debate-on-human-nature-1971|website=[[ONscenes]]|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Clash of the Titans: Noam Chomsky & Michel Foucault Debate Human Nature & Power on Dutch TV, 1971|url=http://www.openculture.com/2013/03/noam_chomsky_michel_foucault_debate_human_nature_power_in_1971.html|website=[[Open Culture]]|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Noam Chomsky debates with Michel Foucault (1971) - Classroom - Art & Education|url=https://www.artandeducation.net/classroom/video/66054/noam-chomsky-debates-with-michel-foucault-1971|website=artandeducation.net|accessdate=6 November 2017|language=en}}</ref>
